<!-- Sida 7 -->

"This must be the place I've always wanted to leave."
—Talia Navarre

<!-- Sida 8 -->

I died a few minutes ago.
Or at least, that was the plan. As
usual in this city, nothing went
according to plan. But I'm getting ahead
of myself. Let me start from the beginning, about
twelve hours ago.

I was eating a late lunch at the Golden
Salon down in Ikonen. A meal consisting of
eggs, pork, sausage and bacon, made
for a hard-working man. With a Redovs
Fat I washed away the greasy fat taste
from my palate. I had no clients
in the afternoon and was planning to visit a
lady acquaintance for some relaxation for body
and soul. It was already here my luck
left me, but I didn't realize it then.

**Behind me came a two-meter refrigerator**
lumbering. A strained breath hit
my neck and a coarse, hairy hand
was placed heavily on my left shoulder.

"Jandaran..." said a hoarse voice, which
broke the calm like a pistol shot at
midnight.

I knew who was standing next to
me. Donner. The man without a first name. One
from the old guard, an ox who had
survived everything from lead poisoning to
being found hanged from the Klemenko Bridge.
You have to respect such a man. The hand
remained on my shoulder. I slowly turned
my head.

"Gabriel Jandaran, the gumshoe?"

The hoarse voice said it more as a
statement than as a question. The breath
smelled of cheap booze and cheap whores.

"Yes, that's me. Who's asking?"

I scrutinized Donner. He wore
an older, rough suit that didn't fit
particularly well, it strained across his
frame. The shirt collar had small,
barely visible, traces of dried blood.
The knuckles on the hand on my shoulder had
fresh bruises and a cut. Donner's
face, as if chiseled by an
epileptic stonecutter, glared at me.
Hell, he was huge.

"The boss wants to talk to you, outside,
now."

**The face was completely expressionless when**
the words came. If I was
correctly informed, Donner was employed by one of
the city's bigwigs, Klarence Gieger, a
magnate in metal and industry, and with
contacts within both the clans and the State.
A man it would be foolish to irritate.

<!-- Sida 9 -->

I nodded briefly, reached for
my hat, laid a twenty on the counter and let
myself be escorted out.

On the street I was led to a gigantic
Concran, extended, probably
bulletproof. It stood on the other side
of the street, all windows were tinted. I saw
my reflection in the shiny, black
lacquer when the back door was opened by a pale
hand. Donner gave me what he surely
considered a careful push forward to
show that I should get into the car.

**The effect was rather that I tumbled**
in and landed on the floor. Behind me
the door slammed shut and the noise from the street
abruptly fell silent. I rose as
dignified as I could, smiled an awkward smile and
sat down on the seat opposite the older,
well-dressed man who quietly observed
me.

"May I offer you something?" he asked
with a cold, strained voice.

"Yes please, a whisky."

**A chilly smile flashed across his**
face. He opened the bar section in the car
and took out a bottle, a good brand.

"How do you take it?"

"In a glass."

The professional smile again.
The eyes didn't smile. With slightly trembling
movements he poured a double for
me. He took nothing himself.

"Mr. Jandaran, I am Klarence
Gieger. I got your name from a mutual
acquaintance, Dr. Yannik Reasescu. You
helped him a while ago and he
said you were quick and discreet."

The gray eyes didn't let go of me with
their gaze. He expertly lit a brown cigarette
and contentedly blew out the smoke in the cabin.
I took a deep swig of the warming
liquid. In the corner of my eye I noted how
Donner remained standing outside the door. There
was a chauffeur in the car. The door on
the opposite side was locked and the handle was
removed. I was trapped in here.

"I remember the case."

It was an old case, one of
the easy ones. Find a family member gone
astray and return the person to
the family. A specialty of mine. I
was lucky that time, picked up the right trail
and followed it to the end, to the treasure
and the reward. Good money.

"I find myself in a similar
situation, Mr. Jandaran."

**Gieger leaned forward and lowered**
his voice. I met him. Felt mint and
smoke in the exhaled air. His mouth was
small with narrow dried lips, yellow
teeth and an almost black tongue.
Under the eyes the skin was stiff and
almost grayish-black—like on a
smoked corpse. The clothes
were of the latest cut, elegant and of high
quality. He wore a wedding ring and at least
two order rings I couldn't place.

"My daughter is missing. I want
you to find her. She is fourteen,
turning fifteen this year."

**Gieger stubbed out the cigarette and handed over a**
photograph of a young woman in school uniform.
Bored expression, well-developed for her age,
light hair, beautiful, defiant face. She
looked older than fourteen, but the city has
that effect. If she was even his daughter,
if she was even fourteen. It's hard to
determine if a man is telling the truth when you
yourself would probably lie if the roles
were reversed. But it didn't matter.
I didn't care about the motives as
long as I got paid in the final act.

"Her name is Derya. I got a call
this morning that she hadn't shown up for
lessons at Todos."

Todos, one of the Inner City's most
prestigious private schools, with boarding school and the
whole package. Sure, thanks. Here there was
money to be milked.

"According to her bodyguard, a bungler who
doesn't work for me anymore, she
disappeared without a trace during the night. If she's
been kidnapped I'm willing to pay whatever
it takes to get her back."

He lit a new cigarette while the gray
eyes locked onto mine. I swallowed and
nodded briefly.

"There are many in Sandukar who wish
me harm, and going through Derya is one
way to strike at my heart."

Reality seemed bad enough,
I decided to believe the story for now.

"You'll get two thousand zovrins per day,
plus a bonus of five thousand if you solve
the case within 48 hours. I don't want
this to leak out to the press or
the police. Understood?"

I nodded again. He seemed somewhat
relieved and drew the smoke into his lungs.

9

<!-- Sida 10 -->

"Keep the photo, on the back is a
phone number you can call when you've
solved this or need something. I
need to get her back."

**The constant problem with wanting**
something. You always risk
failing. Desire makes one unfocused and
weak. But I would do my best. That
a wealthy man's daughter gets kidnapped is a
cliché in this city. But the situation
is never a cliché when it strikes you
yourself.

The rest of the afternoon went like clockwork.
Already then I should have suspected trouble. Nothing
goes that smoothly. The gatekeeper at Todos got
his memory back when his wallet was filled
and he confirmed my suspicion. Derya

**Gieger left the school voluntarily**
shortly before midnight the night before, got
into a car and left the place. No
coercion, no gasp, no violence. I cashed
in a favor at the archives and traced
the car's registration number to an address
in Askan, toward the harbor. The State's control
over citizens is frighteningly accurate in
most cases. The owner of the car, a
guy by the name of Janos Kostin, worked
as a croupier at a popular nightclub
called Chacha Club. A notorious place
where more have entered than have come
out. The watering hole was also known for its
private rooms on the second floor, something that
made my stomach knot up.
Chacha Club is by no means a place
for a fourteen-year-old schoolgirl.

**After maneuvering my way through**
the subway in rush hour traffic I emerged
a block from the club. I found myself
in a run-down part of the district,
with containers, condemned warehouse premises
and worn apartment buildings for bums,
fugitives and criminals. It was almost
deserted but the music from the club could be heard
from far away and several cars, most of
older models, stood outside. Suddenly I felt
watched. I quickened my pace
and entered a doorway and waited.
Nothing was heard. I looked out, backward, but
it was empty. Probably it was my
own nerves playing tricks.

A light snowfall wrapped the wet
streets. I saw my own breath
in front of me. Chacha Club was not a
place I wanted to return to. A
number of my enemies could very well
be there—unfaithful husbands, abusive
swine, ex-cons who had served their
sentences—all could be someone I put
away earlier.

In the darkness of a broken street lamp
I stopped and checked that
the revolver was loaded. I returned it
to the ankle holster. My automatic pistols
were at the office. Five bullets were what I
had if the situation went sour.

**The club was housed in a two-story**
brick building in red. The windows were
barred. The building had previously
been a police station, so it was
freestanding, with parking and alleys
all around. A few years ago
apparently the police had moved after a scandal
when a clan son was found beaten to death and
raped in one of the cells. Who was
behind the deed never came to light, but
according to a source the duty officer,
as well as the constables who picked up the son,
are in the canal somewhere, in concrete and
chains. If you mess with the wrong people in
Sandukar it's often the last thing you do.

**Light from a couple of spotlights cut**
through the snowflakes and passed me.
I couldn't help but let out
a low whistle when I recognized
the registration number—Kostin's car. The same
car that barely a day earlier had
picked up young Miss Gieger. I considered
running after the car and meeting it when
it parked but decided to take
it easy. Observe and act based on
what happened. Think first and not do
anything rash.

**The car stopped right outside the club**
and a slim man in coat and cap got out.
**From the passenger side emerged a**
short, neat figure in a cloak. In the glow from
a street lamp her light hair was visible. She
walked around the car, the man put his hand around
her waist and the two quickly made their way
through the snowfall and in through the door to
Chacha Club.

There wasn't a chance I would
succeed in getting in without drawing
attention. Such miracles don't happen
in this city. Opposite the club
was a solitary phone booth. I jogged
across the empty street and discovered that
luck was with me—the phone worked.

**I had memorized the phone number and my**
stiff fingers dialed to
reach Mr. Gieger. Two trembling signals,
a crackling click and a hoarse voice that
answered.

"Yes, Mr. Jandaran?"

**I was surprised but collected myself**
quickly.

"Donner, Miss Gieger is at Chacha
Club in Askan. Are you familiar with it?"

"Yes."

"So where do I pick up the money?"

There was silence for a few moments.

"You'll get a bonus if you fetch her right
now. Twenty thousand zovrins."

**The hoarse voice was completely without**
emotion. Immovable as a wrecked
diesel locomotive. Greed flared
up within me. Although the voice of reason in
my mind warned against this, the sum
made me feel desire. Desire makes one
unfocused and weak. Greed killed
the voice of reason in just a second.

10

<!-- Sida 11 -->

"Of course. I'll get her. Have the
money ready."
"Yes."
There was a click on the line and it went
silent as the grave. The snowfall had
intensified. I turned up my coat collar and
walked toward my doom.
Under cover of snow and the absence of
streetlights, I circled the building and saw
the kitchen entrance among overflowing
garbage cans and a rusty dumpster. The
snow cover crunched softly as I made my
way forward as quietly as I could. The door
I reached was metal but proved to be
unlocked. The heat and stench of fried
food hit me. Quickly I slipped in,
closed the door and listened. I found
myself in a shabby corridor with bare
concrete walls and cardboard boxes along
the floor. A few meters down to the left
came the clatter of kitchen utensils. Beyond
the kitchen a door was visible, from which
the harsh music could be heard more clearly.
Two bare light bulbs spread their yellowish-
white glow over the corridor as I quickly
made my way past the kitchen without being
discovered. The door to the establishment
had a foggy, round window that I peered out
through. It was packed in there. Rough men
drank beer, played billiards, made pathetic
attempts with harbor whores to get a quickie
for free, but neither Kostin nor Miss Gieger
were visible anywhere. The staircase up lay
a few steps from the door. Quickly I got the
door open without a sound. Luck continued
to smile my way when with a few quick
strides I conquered the solid wooden
staircase and came up into a dimly lit
corridor with a worn red carpet with burn
marks from cigarettes and stains from both
one thing and another. From closed rooms
along the corridor came grunting and
giggling. At one of the doors furthest away
stood Kostin. He looked toward me.
"Desire for twenty thousand has made you
stupid in the head."
**The voice in the back of my head got air but**
I stifled it. Now it mattered. Show that
you can handle this. Take a vacation with
the money. Leave the city for a while. Without
staring down the thin man I advanced
as nonchalantly as I could. No one else
was within sight. Sweat pressed forth on
my forehead, the hat fortunately covered my
eyes. Otherwise Kostin would surely have seen
in them that he was in trouble.
**My right hand moved down into my pants pocket**
and closed around a roll of coins. The roll
lay perfectly in my hand. The fist clenched. Kostin
reacted to me by turning and
meeting up. He raised his hand and was
just about to say something when my fist struck
his nose bone. He blacked out
before he hit the floor. I would get
a serious bruise over my knuckles, but
that was a later problem. The coin roll
returned down into my pocket and I got
out my lockpicks. Still the
corridor was empty. The music rang from
downstairs together with indistinct
voices and cheerful calls. A quick glance
through the keyhole confirmed that the room
inside was occupied. The lock only took
a couple of seconds to open, I stood
up and quietly drew my revolver, grabbed
the door handle, breathed in, saw a bag
of money in my mind's eye and threw
open the door.
Suddenly I realized that all luck was
gone with the wind. I felt like a wild dog
the second before being hit by an
express train.
The room was dim. The bare
walls, with their mold stains and
their flea market art stared at me. At
one wall stood a brass bed. Around
the bedposts sat rusty chains with
handcuffs. But it was not this
that made the air go out of me like a
puncture. Two people stood in the middle
of the room. Miss Gieger was naked except
for a corset and was just in the process
of buttoning the shirt of a large, fat,
unshaven, slovenly man with a cigarette in
the corner of his mouth. Not really a problem
if it weren't for the fact that the man was Sergy
Rulov, Sandukar's perhaps most famous and
brutal gangster boss. No one was ignorant
of his power, connections and ruthless
methods. Suddenly twenty thousand felt like
two cents. I went cold in my soul.
The situation was beyond bad.
"Who the hell are you, you bastard!?"
roared Rulov and surprisingly
quickly pulled out a chrome automatic pistol, a
Calder M2245.
I stood there like a fool. Of all
the millions of people in all of Sandukar,
why Sergy Rulov? Hell! He's
