**Introduction**
Imagine a cocktail party in the penthouse of a black sky-
scraper covered in gothic statues and vaults, to the sounds of
a raging rain that frenetically drums against the tall
window panes. All present are dressed from top
to toe, smiling, conversing. Deals are formed and fortunes
lost during the course of a few spoken words or
a few sips from frosted drink glasses. The people
conceal something ominous, something feverish, within themselves,
which makes them uneasy and on edge, it drives them
to extremes and misfortune. Welcome to Noir.
**What roleplaying is**
Roleplaying in the Noir vein is to build a
story in a group that all group members participate in
with immersion. The story is created together and takes
participants to another place than our own world, where
they act based on the roles they have in the story. This
new world contains elements from our own, but
much is also different – the sky is darker,
people are more nervous and the rain is colder.
In roleplaying everyone wins if the game is exciting,
interesting and fun and if the protagonists handle
the challenges they face in a good way.
The goal is to cooperate and together build up
an engaging atmosphere and story.
One of the participants is the narrator and functions as
rules arbiter and director in one, the others are players
and each have a protagonist that the game is about.
The narrator portrays other characters and speaks
for them in the story. The narrator is not the players' enemy,
even though he/she sometimes portrays narrator characters
who are hostile toward the protagonists.
**The narrator prepares building blocks that the players**
during the game session help to build together into
the story itself. The building blocks consist of narrator
characters, with background stories and mutual relationships,
places and special events that the protagonists
can be faced with. When the protagonists begin
to act the narrator characters will react and
vice versa, and the story is built up by the events that
arise. The goal is for the story after one or
several game sessions to conclude – often through the protagonists
defeating the villain, freeing the prisoner, finding the missing
object or avenging a wrong.
The absolutely most important thing about roleplaying is that it should be
fun. It's good to talk outside the game about what is and
is not fun, and if something goes wrong during the game's course
one must see to doing something about it so it doesn't happen again.

