The city's architectural appearance fascinates many.
The high-rises are built in stone, with lead-framed windows and
grinning stone gargoyles. Marble, copper and steel are also
evident. Several architectural styles are mixed but the Gothic spires
and arched vaults as well as the Art Nouveau movement's beautiful forms are
dominant. In addition to the majestic high-rises there are the
overcrowded workers' districts where the hard-toiling laborers live in soot-blackened brick houses. The industries themselves are
massive constructions of brick, steel and cogwheels. From their
tall chimneys constantly billows a sickly stinking smoke
whose ashes like a shroud of mourning settle over the surroundings.

Above the houses the zeppelins glide forward in silence to the airship
harbors in the city's center. Sandukar is surrounded by a high
wall of black basalt and at its countless gates thorough inspections are conducted by state troops. The circular
shape, the canals' unusual construction and the
massive towers that reach toward the clouds, higher than any
other buildings, reinforce the city's surrealistic feeling.
One can find massive monuments, ancient constructions
and decorated halls where the lineages are said to take their pleasure.

Nowhere in the Empire is corruption as widespread as
in its stronghold. The bureaucrats, civil servants, authority personnel and police force are all severely afflicted,
which causes ordinary citizens to harbor great contempt for
all forms of authority. At the same time they know they must
have cash on hand to escape the greedy inspectors' wrath and be punished for some obscure crime that the
inhuman law book is full of, while the tribunals'
lawyers eagerly lick their lips. One must be
careful so that no one reports one's anti-state thoughts or
expressions. Members of the secret state police, Stapo,
move among the people and monitor, eavesdrop and note
what happens. Should one receive a visit from the black-coated Stapo collectors one evening, one knows it is probably
the last time one sees one's loved ones.

Within the city's sectors the individual's movement is often
restricted and to be able to go to another
sector requires passes and correct identification papers. Subway and canal boats are commonly used, but for longer
journeys trains are required. To get in or out of the city one must take one of the bridge gates, which are guarded by
state inspectors and city guard. The queues at exit and entry
are usually long and patience-trying.

Sandukar is both the dream and the nightmare in
one—a place where one can succeed in reaching the ultimate achievement, but where one just as easily can die a slow and
agonizing death.

**The Empire**

The Empire is the gigantic state where the stories in Noir take
place. It is said that once upon a time war raged in the Empire. The peoples fought against each other in an unending spiral of
violence. Times of peace were short and there was always some realm
that fought to conquer its opponents. When everything fell
under the State's shadow the realms became provinces under
the lineages' rule. Some of the provinces are very rich and
have multiple cities, others are wastelands that are plundered for
their natural resources but otherwise left alone.

The Empire covers thousands of miles and is connected by poorly maintained roads, canals and airship harbors for the zeppelins. If
one wants to travel through the realms one does so most safely by train.
The railway tracks stretch like a spider's web across the Empire and stop at all major stations. This way of traveling
is cheap and fast, moreover the State has good control over
the passengers and exactly where they travel. The rich use
the airships to travel and most places have an
airship harbor with at least one ship's capacity.

Beyond a few larger cities, where the capital Sandukar shines brightest, the realm is fairly barren, meager and desolate. Few people in the cities see much of the wilderness, the pine
forests or the majestic mountains. In the wilderness there are
many hidden things. It is said to be a place for
rebels and outlaws. Likewise many areas stand under direct control of the lineages, who dwell there in their massive estates and castles. Here ordinary people are not given access and what transpires
behind the walls is kept secret.

Despite the world outside the cities being ill-regarded,
here one finds the resources that drive the realms. From the mountains
the iron ore and coal are retrieved, from the forests the timber,
from the fields the grain and livestock. Here and there rise
massive industries where the workers are slaves under the companies.
Usually one only sees the smoke from these in the distance.

Every area within the realm is ruled by a family or clan
from one of the great lineages. Intrigue-making, double-dealing
and machinations are daily fare among the lineages, as they wish to reach as great
success as possible when it comes to riches, power and
prestige. It may well happen at the expense of another lineage or
in the worst case another family within one's own clan.

In the north the war rages against the enemy. The war has been going on for
decades and devours manpower and materiel at a furious
pace, all to reach the next trench and conquer
another bomb-torn ruined city. But the most important thing
is to ensure that the enemy does not succeed in breaking through and destroying the good lifestyle and standard that the State has provided
its subjects with in the Empire.

In the east the war rages against a province that broke free from
the realm. The province is surrounded but its strong armament
and ability for self-sufficiency make it a very
difficult target. Nevertheless it is considered only a matter of time before
it is reconquered.

