**Creating a**
protagonist
To clarify the creation process, here follows a
detailed example that takes into account both game mechanics
and rules as well as the player's thoughts about creating a
personality and emotional life for their protagonist.
**New protagonist**
Marco is going to play Noir and his narrator Petter has
informed him that the intended stories lie close to
classic film noir, with certain supernatural elements.
After talking for a while, the two arrive
at the conclusion that Marco's protagonist should be a shady
figure, with one foot on the side of the law and the other
in the underworld. Some form of consultant who
takes jobs but isn't under anyone's yoke.
Petter says that all protagonists at the start of
the chronicle will begin with Life experience 0,
see page 220.
Step 1: Preparations (p. 27)
Petter gives Marco an empty character sheet while Marco
takes out a pencil and an eraser.
Step 2 & 3: Archetype/background package (p. 27)
In Noir, you're given the option to choose an archetype that becomes
a framework for creation. Marco, however, wants to choose completely freely
without the help that archetypes provide, which is
perfectly fine. Thus Marco also skips step 3,
the background packages.
Step 4: Concept (p. 27)
The protagonist needs to be summarized through a
concept. After some pondering, Marco gives his protagonist 
the concept "Sharp consultant/detective". The protagonist 
is considered well-versed in the world he lives in
(that the protagonist is male has emerged during
the initial conversations), hence the sharp nature. The choice of
consultant/detective as occupation provides dynamism in what
kind of person the protagonist is—one who takes
jobs for payment in various fields.
Step 5: Attributes & attribute values (p. 28)
Now the protagonist's basic data should be set up
through definition of attributes and attribute values.
The nine values available to distribute are 6, 5, 4, 4, 4, 3,
3, 3 and 2. Marco sees the protagonist as a competent
shooter, a guy who can handle himself socially and who isn't completely
clueless. No particular weakness presents itself
spontaneously.

<!-- Page 35 -->

The two highest values, 6 and 5, are placed on Motorics
and Charisma respectively, to create prerequisites for
a shooter who can talk to people. The three 4s are set
on Build, Perception and Insight. The motivation
behind this is that Marco sees the protagonist as well-trained 
and in good shape. Additionally, the protagonist
is attentive to what happens around him and has
a developed gut feeling. Insight provides the ability to resist
social influence and have a grip on the situation so it feels right
to put a relatively high value on that attribute.
Three 3s and one 2 remain now. A 3 is put on Coordination 
so that the protagonist can manage if smooth
movements or brawls are required. The next 3 is put on Creativity 
to give him imagination and resourcefulness. The last
3 is placed, after much deliberation, on Education, as Marco sees
the protagonist as a reasonably well-read person, with
schooling and general education in his background. This means that
the 2 is placed on Will. At first it doesn't feel
so good, but after some pondering and discussions with Petter, Marco
arrives at the conclusion that it becomes a good hook for the protagonist, 
a twist in the personality. A doubting soul behind a
harder exterior.
Marco also takes the opportunity to update the protagonist's 
concept to "Sharp but doubting consultant/detective".
Step 6: Skills & skill values (p. 28)
By doubling an attribute's attribute value you get
how many points you receive to increase the attribute's
associated skills. In Marco's case it looks as follows:
Coordination (3); gives 6 points.
Build (4); gives 8 points.
Motorics (6); gives 12 points.
Education (3); gives 6 points.
Creativity (3); gives 6 points.
Will (2); gives 4 points.
Insight (4); gives 8 points.
Perception (4); gives 8 points.
Charisma (5); gives 10 points.
Marco looks at table 1:2 on page 28 and notes that a
skill value of 4–6 corresponds to "Competent" and a skill 
value of 7–9 corresponds to "Professional". This gives an
indication of what the levels represent.
He begins with the attribute Motorics, where he has 12
points. The three skills under Motorics are Manual dexterity, 
Throwing weapons and Firearms. For seven points the skill 
value in Firearms is raised to 7. Five points remain.
Four of these go to raising Manual dexterity to 4 and the last
point raises Throwing weapons to 1.
After Marco has gone through the rest of the attributes
and skills, the point distribution looks as follows:
Coordination (3): Melee (4), Reactions (1), Mobility (1)
Build (4): Endurance (4), Strength (4), Tolerance (0)
Motorics (6): Manual dexterity (4), Throwing weapons (1), Firearms (7)
Education (3): Humanities (2), Medicine (2), Natural science (2)
Creativity (3): Construction (1), Create (1), Deduction (4)
Will (2): Determination (0), Resistance (1), Sense (3)
Insight (4): Empathy (1), Oppose (3), Streetwise (4)
Perception (4): Intuition (4), Vehicles (0), Awareness (4)
Charisma (5): Charm (1), Leadership (4), Persuade (5)
That the skill values under Education are distributed evenly indicates
a broad general basic knowledge.
That Tolerance has 0 in skill value means that the protagonist's 
body isn't particularly resistant to
diseases, poisons or drugs—probably the protagonist 
has been quite spared from such things since the value
isn't higher.
Since Persuade and Leadership are prioritized over Charm, the
protagonist is quite direct in his approach and doesn't
engage much in diplomatic maneuvering. A thought was born
when the skill value in Leadership was determined, namely
that the protagonist has previously been in the army, for example
as an officer, and that it was there that physique, shooting and leadership 
ability were formed. But due to low skill values in
Resistance and Determination he didn't cope very well with this career, 
he had trouble giving orders in pressing 
situations and couldn't bear the horrors of war.
